  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Learning and Knowledge Development Facility 2.0</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is being discussed with the donor Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency (Sida). Sida has renewed their interest in working with UNIDO in private sector development and skills development based on the successful experiences of the original project.

The project will contribute to establishing inclusive, sustainable, and innovative market oriented vocational training systems and job creation in Africa and elsewhere in the era of the Fourth Industrial Revolution by facilitating knowledge sharing and supporting a wider innovative approach for PPDPs in skills development.

LKDF 2.0 will address the need for skills development among young people by supporting the establishment and upgrading of local TVET training academies in close partnership with the private sector through Public Private Development Partnerships (PPDPs). A PPDP is a way of delivering and funding public services with wider development impact and building local self-reliance and markets. The investment, risks, responsibilities and rewards are shared between the public sector, the private sector and a development partner. The value proposition is that the private sector partners ensure that the curricula and the training are relevant, while the technical partners, such as UNIDO, are uniquely positioned to bring together stakeholders from the public sector, the private sector and the development sector. As a result of the above, PPDPs are well-positioned to serve as role models for curricula accreditation and emulation by other TVET Centers.

The LKDF 2.0 will directly and indirectly provide support to governments, private sector, training institutions, students and trainees, current and future employees as well as investors to build stronger local economies, create jobs and improve working conditions. The intended end result of the intervention is to offer a strong TVET sector with increased efficiency, productivity, quality and competitiveness: students and trainees will improve their technical skills in line with market needs and will be able to apply them to find decent employments in fields linked to their improved skills.

The project builds on the predecessor project &#x2013; LKDF (120212). An important further addition is the inclusion of applying the Market System Development (MSD) approach to project development. Sida is considering this project a pilot for applying the MSD approach to project development in developing Public Private Development Partnerships (PPDP) in vocational training as a further instrument to address the market failure of a mismatch between supply and demand for industrial skills.</narrative>
  </description>
